2. Introduction: The Importance of the Data Science Industry¶

  1. There’s a low supply of workers in the data science field: Many data science positions are available, but there are very few people with the skills required to fill these roles. This means if you have storytelling, quantitative and computational data skills and can communicate effectively and act ethically, you’ll have a competitive edge in securing a job in data science.
  2. The data science field is versatile and broadly applicable: Data science is a very flexible field and can be applied across all types of industries. From banking and education to marketing and nonprofits, nearly every type of organization benefits from having a data science expert on their team who can explore, report on, and monitor data to make better decisions, improve performance, and meet goals faster. So, if you’re wondering what you can do with a data science degree in a specific industry, it’s likely you’ll find an opportunity that resonates with your career interests and values.
  3. A data science career has the potential to make a lasting impact: As a data scientist, you’ll compile, analyze, and extract valuable insights from data. That data has the ability to do many powerful things: detect early-stage tumors, optimize shipping routes, improve athletic performance, and detect fraud, for starters.

3. Why Data Science?¶

According to glassdoor in 2023, out of the 50 best occupations in the United States, Data Science falls at #3 .

Data Scientists made a median salary of 100,910 US Dollars in 2021. The highest paid 25% made 130,770 US Dollars that year, while the lowest-paid 25% made 77,620 US Dollars.

4. Goals with this Analysis¶

After reading several articles about the data science industry, seeing how the job market is looking for more and more employees to fill data science role and how universities are incorporating data science majors as minor, concentrations, and even actual majors for undergraduates. The University of Notre Dame is an example of this. We decided to see if the salaries are reflecting this need for data science roles. Our analysis will mostly be comprised of multiple graphs to visualize how certain features such as size company, location ... affect the salary of the most popular roles within the data science industry.

5. About the Data¶

The first step in this analysis is to choose a data set. After looking over several data sets, we chose this one: Data Science Salaries 2023. This data seemed perfect for this, it had many different feature values such as work year, experience level, company size, company location, salary in usd, etc. We had a lot of things to work with and thus could compare data science salaries in a particular year in relation to company size, for example. The data set also wasn't perfect, so we were able to clean the data before using it.

7. DATA PROCESSING: Cleaning¶

Our data set is pretty big and filled with information and, as we learned in class, cleaning data is an important step (right after collecting the dat)a to make the optimal analysis and to make good predictions. Our step one when it came to cleaning the data was to get rid of duplicates. We decided to get rid of all the duplicates that were on the dataframe. One of the reasons why we decided to remove duplicates is because towards the end we will build a model using linear regression and having duplicates can and probably will add the weights of samples and can cause bias and because duplicates can also make training longer as they'd increase data size.

Our second step when it came to cleaning was to remove irrelevant data. The next data we decided to remove was the employee_residence, we also considered it as irrelevant data since it's the same information as company_location accross all the table.

Our third and final step for cleaning the data was to "detect outliers". As we previous said, we had more than 2000 observation in our data set, we noticed that if we wanted to make a good exploratory analysis we needed to group certain values together. We used the value_counts function to know exactly which data would make a bigger impact if we were to make plot to analyse the data. Certain coutries like the US, CA and IN had higher impacts than say IR, CR and MT. Once we posed that problem, we decided to collapse the coutries that had less than 10 count as other since they were not going to make a big change in our data and they would also overpopulate our graph/plots.

8.2 Graph of Salary vs Year for Top 5 Data Science Jobs¶

In the graph below we are showing the top 5 data science jobs (Data Scientist, Data Analyst, Analytics Engineer, Machine Learining Engineer, Data Engineer) on a graph of salary vs. year. Between 2021 and 2022 we can see that there is a pretty large increase in salary. In 2020 and 2021, when COVID-19 first hit, many jobs took a lot of losses. Many companies were able to go remote while, for data science in particular, it was hard to collect, interpret and predict data. This resulted in a loss in revenue which led to a decrease in salary. Once the world began having control over COVID, and things started to get better, businesses were opening up and actually making money, and companies were going back to in person work. This led to an increase in revenue which would, in turn, result in an increase in salary.

8.3 Salary vs. Year for Each Job Title¶

As future computer and data scientists, we knew prior to looking at this dataset the the US consistently has the highest salaries when it comes to tech careers. This data set solidified that for us. Becuase of this we want to compare the salaries in different locations to see how big of a difference there is. As you can see in this box and whisker plot below, for data science, the US has a much higher average salary. With Canada falling closely behind. The lowest average is India. We are only comparing the countries that have enough salaries to actually create a box, some countries didn't have enough and were creating straight lines and not boxes. We have made plots for this for different job titles.

In the graph below you can see that the average machine learning salary in the US is higher than the data science salary, with about a 15,000 U.S. dollar difference. But then for other countries the average is much lower. The average data science salary in India was about 40,000 U.S. dollars. The average machine learning salary in India is about 20,000. This likely has to do with how much each country values machine learning. The US spends about 10 billion U.S. dollars a year on machine learning, only second to China with 12 billion U.S. dollars. And although the US does pay the most in terms of data science salaries, the demands for data science are much more prominent in other countries.

8.4 Salary vs. Country for each Job Title based on Company Size¶

Here we are looking at the effects that a company's size has on the salaries of its employees. In the graph below we have bar plots for each country with each bar representing the company size. For this plot we are focusing on Data Science Salaries, the distribution is pretty similar across different job titles. It's very interesting to see that medium sized companies are pretty consistently paying more throughout. You would think that a larger company would have more money to give to their employees. However, research has shown that data scientists start bigger at smaller companies. Whereas many job titles show dramatic increases with company size, data scientists at smaller companies earn only slightly less at smaller companies than they do at large companies. And though medium-sized companies employ the fewest workers nationwide, tech workers prefer this size by 44%.

8.5 Salary vs. Year for Data Science Based on Experience Level¶

In the graphs below we are comparing data science salaries based on experience levels. The distribution is pretty much as expected, with executives making the most and entry levels making the least. There’s a pretty large jump in salary for executives between 2022 and 2023. Between October 2021 and October 2022, there was a 26% drop in data science job postings. And then in 2023, there was a pretty significant increase in job postings. We also noticed that for Senior level Data Scientists, between 2020 and 2021, there was a steep decline in salary. We believe that this is due to the aftermaths of COVID-19 and how much it affected so many companies and industries, including tech.

9. LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL¶

After cleaning, evaluating and summarizing our data. We decided to build a linear regression model focused on the company location since it seems to be one of the very important features that affect our data. In the folllowing lines of code, we will predict the value of the salary based on the 5 countries.

How did we pick the 5 countries?¶

Our goal was to find countries that fall in different categories. Some that are more popular, some that fall in the middle, and some that are lower. When we looked at the data set, we noticed that the United States and Canada had the highest popularity and France and India were somewhat in the middle and Mexico was at the top5countries lowest position. We made sure to diversify our independent variable to have a more interesting analysis just like the one in project 3.

In [ ]:
countries =['US', 'CA',
            'IN', 'FR', 'MX']
data3 = data1[data1.company_location.isin(countries)]
data3.head()

res1 = smf.ols(formula="salary_in_usd ~ company_location: work_year", data = data3).fit()
print(res1.summary())

Conclusion: Analysis of the OLS regression Results¶

From this table we can note that, all our independent variables are statistical significant because there p value = 0.000 which is less than a significance leve l of 0.05. We can reject the null hypothesis. We can also see that our all our coefficients are positive, which indicates that as the salaries will tend to increase as time goes by.

# Create a dictionary of the slope 
mappingSlope = {
    "CA":9.724364e+03,
    "FR": 9.695835e+03,
    "IN": 9.677477e+03,
    "MX": 9.707493e+03,
    "US":  9.734262e+03

}
y_intercept1=  res1.params.Intercept 

#create new column representing the salary predictions 
lifeExp_pred1 = []
interaction_residuals = []
for a, x, c in zip(data3['salary_in_usd'], data3['work_year'], data3['company_location']): 
    # getting a single prediction  
    lifeExp_pred_i = x * mappingSlope[c]  + y_intercept1
    #list of life expectation prediction
    lifeExp_pred1.append(lifeExp_pred_i)
    
    # lifeExp_i - lifeExp_Pred_i = mx + b -> x = year    
    interaction_residuals.append(a - lifeExp_pred_i)
  
    #adding 2 new columns to our data 
    # 1 -> residual and life_prediction 

data3['interaction_residuals'] = interaction_residuals
data3['salary_pred1'] = lifeExp_pred1

Looking at our interaction_residual we can conclude that our salaries prediction are too big since some of the residuals are negative. The 1st violin plot shows that the residual for 2023 is lower than the other years. The shape of the distribution is extremely skinny on each end for all our plot and get wider in the middle indicates the salary residuals are highly concentrated around the median. We smees like our residual for small company are always lower than than the medium and large company except for the year 2020,where the median is pretty consistent accross all the different size. 2021 and 2023 have the most distant medians between the small, medium and large size company.
